end

## Required reading
- G'MIC official reference / list of commands (GREYC Lab / D. Tschumperlé, CeCILL) — https://gmic.eu/reference/list_of_commands.html
- gmic-py docs (binding usage; NumPy/PIL/scikit-image interop, GreycLab / myselfhimself, CeCILL) — https://gmic-py.readthedocs.io/
- anthropics/skills (no G'MIC skill present) — https://github.com/anthropics/skills
- No official Anthropic/Claude skill — drive the documented CLI / G'MIC language directly.

## Render
```bash
# install the CLI (preferred headless driver)
brew install gmic

# from scratch (no input): synthesize a 64x64 RGB image
gmic 64,64,1,3 fill_color 255,128,0 -o out.png

# transform an input image with a chained pipeline (the recipe)
gmic input.png -blur 3 -o output.png

# reproducible stochastic filters: inject a seed first
gmic input.png srand 42 fx_freaky_details 2,10,1,11,0,32,0 -o output.png

# verify the deliverable
file out.png   # -> PNG image data, 64 x 64
```

## Failure modes
- Stochastic filters (noise, sketch, freaky_details) are non-deterministic without `srand <seed>` — always inject a fixed seed for reproducible output.
- Output is only byte-stable across runs if the gmic version is pinned — pin via brew / check `gmic version`.
- Python binding (`pip install gmic`) wheels lag behind current Python / macOS arm64 — prefer the CLI for headless CI; fall back to the binding only when wheels exist.
- Pipeline syntax errors abort with a nonzero exit — validate output existence + format (`file`) after every render.
- The CLI can emit video frames / `.obj` meshes too, but this wrapper targets the raster image kind.
